very widely known is an example of the credit scoring system. And so there's a specific score,

00:39:37.760 --> 00:39:42.879
maybe it's your FICO score, there's other credit bureaus, right? So those are not used directly in

00:39:42.879 --> 00:39:48.639
these systems, but they have specific, and insurance companies use credit-based insurance

00:39:48.639 --> 00:39:56.239
scores. So as a part of their business model, these credit broker companies, they sell data

00:39:56.239 --> 00:40:04.560
to companies that say, okay, based on, I have 200 million, I have data of 200 million Americans.

00:40:04.560 --> 00:40:11.280
And I think that based on all this data that I have, this person has a higher mortality risk.

00:40:11.280 --> 00:40:16.000
And so therefore you should not offer them a life insurance policy at this price. You need

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:20.080
to offer it at a higher price. And so those are the kinds of things that we look at. And if you

00:40:20.080 --> 00:40:27.040
sort of take a step back, well, why is, what's, what are the factors that are connected to somehow

00:40:27.040 --> 00:40:32.479
in this credit scoring system that are leading to that, right? So there's baseline levels of things

00:40:32.479 --> 00:40:38.080
like, because of just baseline levels of racial discrimination in this country, for example,

00:40:38.080 --> 00:40:42.479
certain groups have worse mortality outcomes, and it's directly because of discrimination. Now,

00:40:42.479 --> 00:40:47.120
the insurance company didn't do anything there. They're not causing that discrimination. They're

00:40:47.120 --> 00:40:50.639
not causing those health impacts, but those health impacts are still there. So from a business

00:40:50.639 --> 00:40:55.199
perspective, what they don't want to do, what we don't, they don't want to get blamed for that

00:40:55.199 --> 00:40:59.760
because they're not at fault for that. And so what we can do is we can say, okay, well, we know that

00:40:59.760 --> 00:41:05.040
if we're using this credit score, it's going to affect this particular population in a worse way

00:41:05.040 --> 00:41:09.600
at the same value than at this other population. So what we can do is we can say, okay, maybe we'll

00:41:09.600 --> 00:41:15.520
lower this threshold, or we maybe will use a different variable. There's a legal standard

00:41:16.479 --> 00:41:22.479
in the employment context that has to do with an alternative, and I'm going to not say the name

00:41:22.479 --> 00:41:29.040
correctly, but it's an alternative data source, or you have to prove it's like the worst,

00:41:30.800 --> 00:41:35.760
the best possible alternative. So like it's making the, it's able to make the same business decision

00:41:35.760 --> 00:41:39.679
while also not discriminating. So you have to prove the existence of some other factor that

00:41:39.679 --> 00:41:43.600
you could use in order to make the decision that would result in the same business outcome.

